column1: 336006;instagram;2018-09-29 10:27:24;FALSE;"the news has been exceptionally hard for survivors in recent months, and particularly for those following what is happening in the us right now. the incredibly powerful #whyididntreport hashtag that was borne of this shared trauma is so important, and globally relevant. reporting rates for sexual violence are low, and so many survivors fear that they will not be believed.

we want you to know: we believe you. we support you. we do not require a police report to access our services, and nor do any rape crisis centres in the uk. we are here to listen, to hear you, and to help you on your journey of recovery. you don't have to face this alone.

336015;instagram;2018-09-29 10:33:28;FALSE;"with the terrible actions of the us to degrade and abuse women in politics and the legal system it has reminded me of our own engrained sexism and my own experience in science and engineering.
i live with anxiety partly due to nature, partly nurture.

the battle of having to be ""one of the lads"" to be part of the team. to accept the mysogyny in order to work on site because they won't change for me. to feel intimidated daily when i'm the only female on site. to have to walk around with used sanitary products in my bag because they won't provide bins. to be called aggressive and to be told i'm too emotional or on my period when i try to assert authority. to have been silenced when i spoke up about sexual harassment to the point where i felt i had to find a new job.

i could go on for days, and the worst thing about it is the silence of all these men who say they are ""good guys"". if you are silent, you are complicit. if you don't address mysogyny in your male peers then you are responsible for maintaining the culture.
it is your obligation to speak up to casual sexism as well as when it is overt and abusive.

because of the time sensitive nature, given whatâ€™s going on, i rushed to write this for the @nytimes without stopping to think of the toll it would take on my own emotional well-being. in the past three days i have been anxious, depressed, nauseous, sobbing and holding on to #littlehands so much and so tightly she is highly annoyed! (she has no idea why and thinks itâ€™s mommyâ€™s hormones.)

but the outpouring has been such a salve, a balm to my frayed nerves and feeling flayed. when you sublimate something for over thirty years, you get pretty good at it. even very close members of my family have been utterly shocked and saddened. my mom has had to deal with her guilt. but she and i have made peace with our history. she, like most parents, has done the best she could.

doing this very difficult thing has been for me a necessary step. i am no longer scared of ghosts. i hope that my story and those of literally millions of others can contribute to how we address this harrowing topic in our culture. so many of you have messaged me with your own experiences and i am truly sorry that we share this trauma. but the only antidote is taking our power back by being as open as possible, and sending young girls and women the message that there is no shame in speaking out.

what happens to a womanâ€™s body should be her choice at all times, and in all cases. we must exert dominion over our own bodies. that whatâ€™s at stake here. and thatâ€™s why i shared what i did. thank you for your support.

336107;instagram;2018-09-29 12:02:04;FALSE;"i wrote this book to give other abuse survivors a simple roadmap to begin their healing process. many books on this topic are quite complex, but this cuts the fat to go to the meat: how can i heal. .
this is for male and female survivors.
how can i speak to a new lover about my sexual triggers?
how can i ever forgive my mother for beating me like that?
how can i ever have a relationship and trust anyone?
why is my money situation so messed up? .
you will find some answers here and more importantly practical tools, especially if you download the additional free workbook i offer inside of this book. .
this book is for survivors of physical, mental or sexual abuse. you will find the practices apply for many types of experience. .

i found i had to go to many sources to piece together why so many different areas of my life were not working the way i wanted them too. i realised that my current relationships, and my money issues and my body image were all linked to my low self esteem. .
and when you shift your core self? everything else changes for the better. .
i pray it serves you, please share this post xx
link in bio, or find on amazon: jay diamond: abuse to abundance.

336108;instagram;2018-09-29 12:02:05;TRUE;;"this is so terrifying. iâ€™m going to court cause i finally found the strength and courage to engaged charges against my ex narc and violent boyfriend. i have many proofs but still i donâ€™t know if itâ€™s gonna be enough since we live in a society where people donâ€™t feel concerned about anything if it doesnâ€™t happen to them. #repost @whywomendontleave with @get_repost

this. is. wrong. period. i wish that no one ever had to go through this. going through this is hell. there is a reason victims don't report abuse, especially sexual abuse. i told the police my husband raped me, i didn't expect anything to happen.  i was sent down to the hospital to have a rape kit done. it was one of the single worse experiences. first i had to wait for hours for a nurse trained to do the exam to show up. hours. when she showed up she was cold, rude and short with me. the rape exam is extremely invasive. i had already been violated in so many ways already. i choose to end the exam. we had sex. we were married.  i was forced. it was his word against mine. i was fortunate that i had taken pictures of the physical abuse i had endured over the years. even though i didn't report it to the police (i was too afraid) i took pictures,  showed the date in the photo with a newspaper, printed the photo out and kept the photos in a safe location at a relative's house.  i was able to use those photos in court for my restraining order.  document everything. everything! it's so important.  facts, and proof are necessary.

336111;instagram;2018-09-29 12:02:39;FALSE;"two days ago with a quivering voice, i heard dr. christine blasey ford admit she was terrified and proceed with her testimony anyway.  i have always been in support of the me-too movement, i have shared my own story. but something about her courage made me want fight for those who havent. the memories of my own little world of abuse arose. the heart beat. the agony. the weight and shame of sexual abuse is enormous.

its happened more than once to me. from age 4 to 16. in momentary awkward ways that made me feel embarrassed and small. it's happened in catastrophic ways that left me sobbing with a sense of shame that sat in my stomach for years. my abuser wasnt a stranger, acquaintance, co-workers, he was my grandfather, also a pastor who led a thriving mexican church. i thought we were friends, buddies, i even convinced myself all this was how he loved me.â €

well i reported it, unknowing that i would the day i was questioned by cps, ....even though my entire family lived in denial, as well as the entire independent fundamental baptist world around me. my culture then blamed me, and i also blamed myself. only two people fought for me then...and have steadily stood by me through the years. (thank you alan and yvette latta) â €

i do not say any of this as a victim but as a survivor and fighter. each time i get back up from this rage, a wound is healed, and i learn how to love and trust again. its been a life long journey of healing and trust.

to all the survivors- you're not alone. although the world might try to deny, accuse, attack, berate and belittle- i hear your story, i believe your truth and i stand with you. courage is contagious. thank you to all of the hundreds of thousands who speaking up and speaking out today.

surely we've all seen the name dr christine blasey ford dominating our news cycles and our social feeds. how many of you watched her testimony?
i did, and it gave me chills.

much like anita hill did many years ago, dr christine blasey ford saw a dangerous and abusive man about to be appointed to one of the most powerful positions in the us, and she decided the right thing to do was to tell the truth.
her truth was that when she was 15 years old, this ""man"" sexually assaulted her and she managed to escape before he raped her, all while his friend laughed and watched on.

much like in the case of anita hill, dr ford's life has been turned upside down by her honesty. she and her parents have been subjected to constant abuse and accusations of ulterior motives, to the point that they have had to leave their homes and she has security details.

if you haven't watched dr ford's testimony, please do. she is quiet and polite, and yet immeasurably powerful in her testimony. she has become the voice of so many that have long been to afraid to report or have had their accusations dismissed. many women have spoken about their own assaults for the first time as the result of dr ford's tremendous bravery.

perhaps this time we will truly listen. perhaps this time she will be believed. perhaps this time her being believed will have long lasting consequences, not just for this case, but for all the cases in which the truth of victims is dismissed or minimised.

i am sick of feeling ""lucky"" that i have not been raped or subjected too major sexual assault. even in writing that i feel my minimisation of the all too common ""minor"" assaults i have been subjected to. enough is enough.

336138;instagram;2018-09-29 12:26:05;FALSE;"saw this tweet posted by what is probably a â€œliberalâ€ account. most likely re-posted by someone as a gesture of what i imagine to be some form of solidarity with #christineblaseyford historic hearing. but when i saw this it operated as a one liner that became an unintended personal trigger. whether itâ€™s online or irl social media can either enrich or narrow our singular points of view. i can not directly live in someone elseâ€™s shoes- but because of the openness and willingness of friends, strangers, and public figures who use social media to educate and share their truths- i can challenge myself to learn how to widen my own scope. finding both â€œcorroborating and exculpatory evidenceâ€ that allows me to also keep my privileges in check. â€¢

people are dying and suffering everyday in ways we do see and in ways we donâ€™t- which relates to the mental/physical/public health crises in this country (including homelessness/poverty). we literally hear about everything from tragic stories to micro aggressions from marginalized voices everyday. and on different levels, people choose to care and people also callously choose not to care that â€œthe systemâ€ continues to be broken ( or designed the way it was intended) for so many period. this image made me think of erica garner and her story. while not directly a #metoo narrative the way people would prefer, it is about forms of activism and the disproportionate tolls it takes on those who struggle to be heard in relation to accountability. dr. ford answered more than once that when deciding to come forward that she was continuously weighing the cost/benefits until both the press flooded her regular life (even so far as her mistaking a reporter for one of her students in her classroom) and a leaked letter made it difficult not to. garner, who continued to seek justice, challenging the same system (like thousands if not millions of others in this timeline) ultimately came at the expense of her health. i thank @rachel.cargle for recently sharing an article about activism/self care which helped to enrich my own understanding about these correlative struggles. â€¢

336186;instagram;2018-09-29 13:01:04;FALSE;"you don't have to be trafficked to be a victim of sexual violence. 17,700,000 women have reported a sexual assault since 1998. . . these numbers make my heart so heavy and even heavier with the knowledge that some of these women include our friends, family, co-workers and ourselves. .

freeleaf is at work to bring healing and restoration to so many women who, maybe like you or someone you know, have been deeply hurt by sexual violence. we empower them to know they can choose courage over comfort and share their experience so they can start the healing process. .
the amazing thing about the #metoo movement is that a huge conversation is happening to reshape the way we see sexual violence and bring resources and healing to individual women (and men!). .
if you or someone you know has been sexually assaulted, there is zero shame in sharing your experience so you can get the help you need and hopefully see justice brought to your situation! .

the second time it happened, i was 23. three years ago this past wednesday. he was a ""friend"" of the family and someone i respected and admired. most people i told questioned me: ""what were you wearing?"" ""were you drinking?""
why didn't you run?"" ""why didn't you hit him? you're strong"" ""why did you put yourself in that situation? you are smarter than that""
people that knew me!!! how would i ever consider coming forward if my own friends and family were doubting my credibility?
i believe you #drford. i believe you because it happened to me and i don't think i would have had the courage to go through what you went through yesterday.

no justice. that is the constant cry fromÂ friends and families of victims as countless cases are left unresolved and ignored.
marita growing thunder, a 19-year-old murdered and missing indigenous women (mmiw) activist fromÂ montana, has experienced lack of justice â€“ five times.

in the early 2000s, maritaâ€™sÂ aunt died. although yvonneâ€™s death was officially recorded as an overdose, marita claimsÂ her aunt had been beaten. â€œall her fingernails had been pulled out. she was unrecognisable when we put her in the coffin. her body was black and blue and swollen.â€ marita also suggests there were four unrelated deaths in her family which police did not investigate. her fatherâ€™s aunt, henry, her grandfatherâ€™s sister, shirley k, and two female cousins that her mother grew up with.

336227;instagram;2018-09-29 13:20:04;FALSE;"#1in5women will or have experienced sexual violence in their life.
with national #domesticviolencemonth approaching, we wanted to take a moment to say #hertruth is #notyourassumptions.
#ibelieveher! who cares how long it takes her to say â€œ#metoo!â€ i #trusther #basicmemoryfunctions.
#sheissomeone! #sheismorethan a sister, mother, daughter, or wife.
how dare you ask â€œwhy did you wait so long?â€ - â€œ#whydidyoustay?â€ - or â€œhow do you know it was he?â€ october is also #antibullyingmonth, #believesurvivors and stop harassing these #bravewomen!

as sara erdmann stated â€œi will never understand why it is more shameful to be raped than to be a rapist.â€ it's time to #endsexualabuse. every 98 seconds an american is sexually assaulted yet the all seeing eye and blind eye of justice always seems to overlook the #testhermony of #resilientwomen.
in case you missed it: â€œ#shessomeone!â€ we have no room for #rapeculture, beyond a shadow of a doubt, we #believewomen. case and point: #whatifgodwasaher?
would you still mistreat her? would you still deny her truth?
when over a dozen women come forth with the same accusation, would that be enough to be considered beyond a reasonable doubt or would you still want more proof?
in a world that silences women, you gotta #supportsurvivors when they speak up without fear of reproof.
here's the naked truth: the system is filled with men that raped women protecting men that raped women all the while of putting the women who've been raped on trial.

who cares how many drinks she drank? who cares how good she looked in that outfit? a women does not have to be modest to be respected. when did her sex appeal become an open invitation?! drinking is not a crime, rape is! hell yeah she looks hella sexy, yet still her body is not yours to defile!

dear women, i adore youâ€¦ not for your fabulous physique or wiles, i adore your propensity to push through in this patriarchal society that perpetually attempts to push you down, i adore you for your ability to cry at night yet greet each day with a smile. -stevie #artisactivism #poem

336241;instagram;2018-09-29 13:23:00;FALSE;"i couldnâ€™t count on all your fingers and toes the amount of times from the age of 21 and under i allowed someone to make me believe that their anger, their fury, the screaming and verbal assault, including physical reactions were somehow my fucking fault. dare i say to the point where i believed i mustâ€™ve deserved it.

2/28 â€œi was born on the island of dominica in the caribbean and raised in the bronx, nyc from the age of 4.
at the age of 7 i was raped and thereafter, sexually molested. i was verbally abused and spiritually beaten down from the age of 8 to 16.

it was as if a war was being waged upon me on every level and i had no protection.  god brought to me countless angels which included one in the form of beethovenâ€™s 5th symphony.  in this music is my story. it spoke directly to me and said marie-claire,  you can make it.

with the help of two great therapists and a strong will to survive, i made it through. after years of severely stuttering from trauma, i discovered my voice, and singing became my saving grace.  it brought me so much joy, it brought me healing and it brought me peace.

i strongly believe in the telling and sharing of my story because it is healing.  i believe that my story could help others going through the same thing. it has taken a tremendous amount of strength and forgiving to get to this point and at 48 years old, i now feel finally ready to share the gift of my contralto voice with the world, â€”unapologetically, unashamedly and with love, so much love.â€
â€” marie claire giraud  48 years old.

336283;instagram;2018-09-29 13:53:41;FALSE;"""kavanaugh is going to get confirmed, we all know that. a lot of women will be very angry. some might even take to the streets. but this won't be the tipping point. there won't be a tipping point, there never is. there will just be the subterranean lava flow of women's anger - slow, blistering, savage and inexorable. we'll go to bed angry, we'll get up angry, we'll drink our coffee and fix the kids' breakfasts angrily, we'll drive thru car line and to work angry, our male colleagues will ask each other if we're on the rag, we'll eat silent lunches with rage and we'll pick up groceries on the way home with vengeance on our hearts. we'll kiss our partners and our kids goodnight wrathfully. we'll cry hot, silently screaming tears in the middle of brushing our teeth. we'll go to bed angry. we'll get up angry... nothing will seem to change for you. but the mother of a 32 year old  man will suddenly snap at him to ""grow up!"" when he complains that he's pretty sick of frozen dinners lately. that quiet chick 3 cubicles down will show up out of nowhere and tell a gathering of dudebros that she'll report them to hr if they don't shut up. they'll call her a bitch under their breath as she turns around, but she won't care. the teenage daughter will ask her dad if he'd still find it funny if she was the punchline in his favorite joke. he'll scold her for talking back and look at his wife, who will look back and say nothing. another daughter will say nothing to her father - ever again.

the anger will shift, seismic but unseen. before the lava used to burn us to ash on the inside. it's bubbling over now. enough of us have ripped open our bodies to let the boiling soil of our lives out that the heat itself causes fires. sure, you can put one or two out at a time. a single flame is easy to catch. but the lava is elemental and everywhere. kavanaugh will be confirmed. and in less than a generation he'll be a petrified ash fossil, frozen in a rictus of agony in the new pompeii. nothing will seem to have changed, until it's too late. the lava of our anger is going to cover the earth and bury you."" -audra alexander

336316;instagram;2018-09-29 14:08:57;FALSE;"my article on instituting a sexual harassment code of conduct is out in this month's print edition of dj mag now. .

as we have seen over the last few months, weeks and even days, sexual harassment remains one of the most harmful and challenging issues of our time. it's currently dividing american government and society, and has at times torn at the fabric of the dance music community. .

though i have never experienced sexual harassment firsthand, i have come to learn, as many men have, just how pervasive it is in the lives of the women we love. with this in mind, i asked women what they thought should be done to curtail harassment and discrimination on dance floors and in the workplace of the electronic music industry.

women like meg wilhoite from female:pressure were incredibly helpful and patient in helping me understand this issue in so many new ways, and for that i'm incredibly grateful. and the women of the we have voice collectiveâ€”who created the sexual harassment code of conduct for their jazz communityâ€”were immensely helpful in guiding me through their process in creating the code. and carly wilford of sister collective, who bravely spoke to me to help me understand the issue as part of the wider discussion around mental health in electronic music. i could not have written this without them. .

as midland recently said, ""this is a very good time for men to step back and listen to women and their stories."" that's what i have tried to do here, and will continue to do in the hopes that we can soon see real change. thank you for reading. .

column1: 336322;instagram;2018-09-29 14:11:03;TRUE;;"deep bow of gratitude to dr. christine blasey ford. the amount of fear she must be feeling to voluntarily walk into the fire, in order to speak her truth...to have to relive her trauma over & over again...is unimaginable. it's like a modern day witch hunt, except for literal fire burning her at the stake, it is lies, ignorance, disbelief, scorn, lack of empathy, chauvinism, objectification, and some f'ed up slander of a biblical text that men have the right to ""own"" women & do to their bodies what they please, irregardless of the consequences. she is standing up against insanity. millennia of being unable to reason with the unreasonable. dr. christine blasey ford and every single person (female, male...all genders) who have spoken up, from privately confiding in a friend to public forums, open themselves up with the risk of being abused again...emotionally & verbally...they risk being told by others that they are the insane ones & that they are less than, that they must have provoked it or actually really wanted it since they were dressed ""inappropriately."" they risk being told their truth is not valuable. it takes bravery to stand up & speak your truth just in day to day situations...i.e in a board room voicing a vision you see for your company that no-one else does. but it is an extreme act of courage...it is heroic...to voice being sexually abused & risk being violently attacked again through the lack of respect & compassion of the toxic & entitled patriarchy. to everyone who has ever spoken out loud their truth & those who do not feel safe enough to speak up, i believe you, i bow to your strength & courage for continuing to live, you are still here & thats audacious. i see you & you are so worthy, you are enough & there are many people, myself included, fighting to right the unspeakable wrongs you have endured. to create a world where the only thing insane is not believing 336323;instagram;2018-09-29 14:11:14;FALSE;"i am one of those women in the #metoo movement. a survivor who had a brief reminder this week about my past, my experience and my story of sexual harassment which took place 13 years ago.
it happened during my first year of university. there was no witness and no material evidence. he was a friend. i never thought it would happen to me.
i wondered who would believe me. i wondered who i could trust. i wondered what i did wrong. i wondered how people would react.
within a few weeks after it happened, i became bipolar, went through periods of depression and developed a sense of generalized anxiety.
it was traumatizing. i felt violated and uncomfortable. i felt scared and unsafe. i walked around the world in fear. i felt alone.

some women are brave enough to talk about it. other women have no idea what it is like to go through something like this. it may not be trending, but the unpublicized stories and mental health of women of colour matter too.
many minority women, immigrant women, women of colour and young girls who are victims of abuse suffer alone, in silence. they deserve our support; not our judgement.
i eventually found hope, healing and happiness. i regained my confidence and learned to trust the world again.
becoming a mother of two little girls has made me feel more empowered to share my experiences as a south asian woman and as a mother.

336325;instagram;2018-09-29 14:11:35;FALSE;"in todayâ€™s ask kelsey i speak about what to do when your fears, worries, and concerns take over. when youâ€™re not just a little upset, but you are starting to spiral out of control.
you may not even know why. you may just feel a sense of panic and be on high alert for anything that might bring you harm, real or imagined.
from the politics in the united states to the #metoomovement to our own complicated personal lives, its easy for our old patterns of fear to take over.
if you find yourself steeped in anxiety, do your best to love yourself in that state.
your state of panic is not a call for judgment and it is not a reason to beat yourself up.
if you are humming with anxious energy, it is a call for more love.

336329;instagram;2018-09-29 14:12:16;FALSE;"for someone awakening to the trauma of his or her past:
for everything under the sun there is a time.
this is the season of your awkward harvesting,
when the pain takes you where you would rather not go,
through the white curtain of yesterdays to a place
you had forgotten you knew from the inside out;
and a time when that bitter tree was planted
that has grown always invisibly beside you
and whose branches your awakened hands
now long to disentangle from your heart.
you are coming to see how your looking often darkened
when you should have felt safe enough to fall toward love,
how deep down your eyes were always owned by something
that faced them through a dark fester of thorns
converting whoever came into a further figure of the wrong;
you could only see what touched you as already torn.
now the act of seeing begins your work of mourning.
and your memory is ready to show you everything,
having waited all these years for you to return and know.
only you know where the casket of pain is interred.
you will have to scrape through all the layers of covering
and according to your readiness, everything will open.
may you be blessed with a wise and compassionate guide
who can accompany you through the fear and grief
until your heart has wept its way to your true self.
as your tears fall over that wounded place,
may they wash away your hurt and free your heart.
may your forgiveness still the hunger of the wound
so that for the first time you can walk away from that place,
reunited with your banished heart, now healed and freed,
and feel the clear, free air bless your new face.

336344;instagram;2018-09-29 14:20:57;FALSE;"i've read women's comments. yes, women! who think a survivor has to relive her experience a certain way to actually be truthful, to be traumatized. they expect them to cry, to be overly emotional...or it's fake, it's rehearsed, it's calculated. she can't be successful (clearly, not traumatized) or a psychologist (she knows how to play the system and she's very calculating in how to manipulate, they say). she can't ever smile or show joy (she's faking it, it's not real, it's all a plot).

look at me. i don't cry anymore about my trauma (unless i'm in my own healing session). i am successful and i will continue to be successful in all my endeavors because i refuse to give those perpetrators and cowards any more of my power. i studied psychology to understand myself,  to understand others, to heal myself, to heal others, to make sense of the fucked up shit that has happened in my life and countless others.

i smile because still i rise, i lift myself and others up. because i am a warrior that will fiercely protect her family and i am proud of everything i've been through that i wouldn't let tear me down. so i smile in satisfaction knowing that i'm doing better, i'm raising my children better, i'm being a great spouse and citizen. because i'm setting my past on fire and i'm setting my spirit free!

have you ever been to a funeral and seen someone smile? why do they smile? often we recount positive, uplifting stories and memories of our deceased loved ones. so yes, even in the face of trauma, in fact especially in the face of trauma, we can smile! because there's hope, there's life on the other side. .

ğŸ–¤i had an aunt ask me last night at shabbat dinner why women wait so long to speak out. my mom shared her experience with sexual abuse/assault. i shared mine, 1 of which i'd never told my mom. i shared others' stories. she then remembered...that's right, we weren't supposed to speak up. we'd be blamed or shamed.

#this #truth #surviver #metoo #timesup #nomoresilence #enoughisenough #motherhood #womensupportingwomen #onevoice #wewillbeheard #istandwithher #womenmatter #women #postpartum #pregcy #mentalhealth #riseup #iamyou #believesurvivors";"i have read women's comments. yes, women! who think a survivor has to relive her experience a ceain way to actually be truthful, to be traumatized. they expect them to cry, to be overly emotional...or it is fake, it is rehearsed, it is calculated. she can not be successful (clearly, not traumatized) or a psychologist (she knows how to play the system and she's very calculating in how to manipulate, they say). she can not ever smile or show joy (she's faking it, it is not real, it is all a plot).

look at me. i do not cry anymore about my trauma (unless i am in my own healing session). i am successful and i will continue to be successful in all my endeavors because i refuse to give those perpetrators and cowards any more of my power. i studied psychology to understand myself,  to understand others, to heal myself, to heal others, to make sense of the fucked up shit that has happened in my life and countless others.

i smile because still i rise, i lift myself and others up. because i am a warrior that will fiercely protect her family and i am proud of everything i have been through that i would not let tear me down. so i smile in satisfaction knowing that i am doing better, i am raising my children better, i am being a great spouse and citizen. because i am setting my past on fire and i am setting my spirit free!

336376;instagram;2018-09-29 14:34:28;FALSE;"you can look at the top players in the comedy game (#kevinhart, #kattwilliams, #mikeepps) and see that even at the highest level, there's brutal competition. now imagine what it's like for the thousands of would be and upcoming #comics who are competing for opportunities.
add to this this the fact that opportunities are further limited accross #race and #gender lines. (in both directions)
now layer the dynamics between bookers and promoters.

as if that wasn't enough, even in the final moments before taking the stage, it's not uncommon to get approached by audience members threatening to #heckle you and call you out if you fail to make them #laugh.
so, why would anyone want to be the court jester when the world is so quick to be off with your head.
we know that #fear of public speaking is considered the number one fear among a societies population. yet, we do it in the most hostile environments.
we know that even though some people can't wait to for an opportunity to catch you slipping, most of them secretly imagine themselves on stage garnering the attention.

and we know the power of the spoken word can change the world. let's not forget it was #hannibalburess, a #comedian, that set fire to #billcosby and the #metoo movement. the effects of his performance are directly impacting #brettkavanaugh, the #supremecourt nominee as we speak. think about that for a moment........ in a world where #freedom of speech is not so free, and constantly under attack, comedians continue to maintain a greater freedom of expression, to mock and to criticize.
comedians keep the society in check. and with mainstream news outlets pushing headlines as opposed to real information, comedians remain one of the few sources of the cold hard, #unfiltered truth.
oh. as for the photo. a wonderful young lady kept interjecting during my set so i took a knee in protest.

336397;instagram;2018-09-29 14:39:17;FALSE;"this woman is incredible. she has endured a wave of despicable hate and anger. why? because she spoke out against appointing the man who assaulted her to the us supreme court.
i've been keeping a bit quiet because i'm not american but you know what? screw it.
there is an epidemic not just in the us, but throughout the world. it's called rape culture.
throughout the entirety of recorded history there have been stories of mistreatment and dehumanization at the hands of men. there have also been stories of the women who rose up against it.
however in the past millennia it seems that no matter how many steps we take as a society the world refuses to move forwards in its treatment of women.
just look at the poisonous attitudes that are so pervasive in our society that we are conditioned to believe are normal; ""boys will be boys""
he's only mean because he likes you""
you shouldn't have been in the park alone""
why didn't you come forward before""

you don't want to ruin his life do you?"" social media has only fuelled the problem. women on the internet are constantly met with harrassment, threats and unwanted sexual attention just for being there.
this is not even touching on the rise in sexual harrassment and sexual assault of women in public places. if i go into detail on that i will be typing all night.

oh, and i am an able bodied, mentally capable white woman. i face none of the additional bullshit thrown at the disabled, the mentally challenged, the trans community and women of colour. i am fucking privileged in this shitstorm of behaviour.
we as a society, we as a united world need to address these attitudes. things need to change. and as the #metoo movement and now dr ford have demonstrated, we are ready and willing to fight for it.
sorry not sorry for the rant. i have a lot of thoughts on this topic.

336414;instagram;2018-09-29 14:47:57;FALSE;"if youâ€™ve been a victim of trauma, sexual assault, rape, abuse in any form i believe you. i stand with you. i see you. i hear you. iâ€™ll fight for you. i love you.

do i believe something must be done & need to change? absolutely. do i believe using our voices to spread judgment, blame, hate, and shame about men as a species is the answer? absolutely not. separating men from women or women from men - separates us as humans. we are not separate. strip us down to bones and energy and we are all one. both masculine and feminine are so importantly equal. and both live within each of us.

iâ€™m always asking myself â€œhow can i live from my highest selfâ€ especially when i feel someone else has wronged me. and that answer is always; living, walking, and speaking through love. not the love weâ€™re taught in society. not the one with conditions: â€œiâ€™ll love you only if you do _____, iâ€™ll love and accept you only if you donâ€™t do ______.â€
true love doesnâ€™t have conditions, and itâ€™s one of the hardest practices. it is also the most powerful force on this planet. it is how we can heal. it is how we can create change. .

this does not mean that we lie down, accept things that harm us, or donâ€™t stand up and rise. it means we do it in a way that is out of love not hate. unconditional love. it means we see other people as ourselves and stop separating by gender, race, or even beliefs. the evil in this world is like a fire, spreading and burning everything it touches. lashing out in hate and judgment is like air to the flame. all of us are being burned. not just the ones we hate. it will only feed more hate, more judgment, more suffering. love is like water, washing over the flames and smothering them, putting them out, and nourishing the soil so that something new and beautiful can rise from the ashes. .

fall in unconditional love with yourself. see others through a lens of love without conditions, and watch how the world changes. if we truly want to create change, we must stand up and rise from a place of love. a place of our highest selves. a place where the suffering weâ€™ve endured can no longer spread, because it can no longer survive. .

column1: 336417;instagram;2018-09-29 14:48:33;FALSE;"i never really thought about the word ""triggered"" meant until i saw this comment (and i'm mostly paraphrasing): so many women are coming forward ""crying assault"", & i'm not saying what happened to them ""wasn't wrong"", but i think it's ""taking away from women"" who were actually raped. .

let me tell you why i wasn't ""truly, genuinely and violently raped"": the first time, he broke into my house while i was in the shower. when i came out of the bathroom in a towel he was standing outside he door waiting for me. he forced me into the bedroom, bent me over, facedown, on the bed & while he was trying to pull my towel off, i managed to grab my phone & hit call on the first number i could get to & started screaming. he stopped, but on his way out of the room he got so mad, he punched a hole in my bedroom door.

the second time the same person tried to rape me i wasn't home alone. my children, who were very young at the time, were upstairs asleep. he had me pinned on the floor with all his weight on top of me & had already ripped my pants off. when i realized he wasn't going to stop, i got desperate and started screaming my son's name, hoping that if he woke up & came downstairs, my attacker would stop & leave. it worked.

are my experiences any less important or traumatic because i wasn't actually raped? thousands of women & men coming forward with stories like mine are often times the reason people who were raped have the courage make their assaults public. don't ever dismiss or insinuate that someone's trauma is less than or invalid or in some way hurting the cause because it wasn't as bad as someone else's. a person that would say something like that has either never experienced assault or thinks it's no big deal. everyone deals with it differently. some people convince themselves it's normal or not a big deal. others need therapy the rest of their lives.
i got lucky. i was able to stop my attacker. i didn't have nightmares or depression or suicidal thoughts. does that mean my story shouldn't be heard?

of course, until very recently, i was in denial. i still can't believe it actually happened. **cont'd in the comments**â¬‡ï¸";;en;;;;;;0;;lady__dmc;Destinee;;0;False;4;0;0;15;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/0f3f1617d275f52b66d06a175e45d5a8/5D192AF1/t51.2885-15/e35/41468632_166608777589838_6381807445057438361_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"i never really thought about the word ""triggered"" meant until i saw this comment (and i am mostly paraphrasing): so many women are coming forward ""crying assault"", & i am not saying what happened to them ""wasn't wrong"", but i think it is ""taking away from women"" who were actually raped. .

336418;instagram;2018-09-29 14:48:35;FALSE;"itâ€™s been a tough week, friends. the supreme court hearings have been so painful to listen to; itâ€™s exhausting hearing the experiences of women/survivors being ignored. â €
itâ€™s also always a little hard on my mental health as the days get a little shorter and the mornings get a little darker. â €

i never told anyone. let me repeat that. i never told anyone. not my parents. not my best friend. not the police. not a doctor. because i couldnâ€™t accept it. even though inside my soul was literally crushed and i felt dead. even though i knew it was wrong. even though i logically knew i was raped, i wouldnâ€™t allow myself to accept that reality. i wouldnâ€™t allow myself to say it. saying it out loud would make it real. i couldnâ€™t come to terms with it.
my latest project is called â€œ#metoo: a collection of true story crimes against women.â€
i am still collecting stories. submissions will be accepted until december 31, 2018.
if you have a story that you would like to include email me at mchillstromauthor@yahoo.com.
all stories will be listed as anonymous submissions.
the types of stories i am looking for include personal experiences of:
-i will accept other topics if they fit in with the theme as well.
through writing my own stories i have found peace and strength.
i hope others will find this as well along with the knowledge that they are not alone.
proceeds from the sales of this collection will be donated to help sexual assault survivors.

this work is dedicated to all female authors. it is known that the world of art, like many other branches of social life, belongs to men. men write, men embody, men choose what is brilliant, what is not.
what is it like in this world for women authors: writers, poets, screenwriters and directors? no wonder the last massive movement in defense of women's rights
#metoo appeared in the creative environment. how does it feel to not be taken seriously only on the basis of gender?

creative people burn in their work, and therefore any negative for them is almost fatal. any criticism can finish, any refusal is a blow. and how many women were disappointed in their talent after the first refusal or criticism. how many were told that their place is in the kitchen. and so the talent goes into the deep underground and the masterpieces lie in a pile on the table. brightness and passion vanishes from such women`s lives but boredom comes, then melancholy and bitter regret for their fate.

why would farmers hurt their animals? the simple answer is because they can. there should be no surprise here, the whole system is built on oppression, cruelty, suffering and death.
so many times people say that farmers treat their animals like family. unfortunately this is not an isolated incident.

336529;instagram;2018-09-29 15:30:31;FALSE;a little morning perspectiveâ€¦ ****trigger warning: sexual assault**** who will love me? â€¦i asked myself after i reported being sexually assaulted to the police. my body now tainted and disgusting.
who will love me? â€¦i asked myself after they found him. because i reported my case to the police too late, the predator was found sexually assaulting another woman. clearly it was my fault.

who will love me? â€¦i asked myself sobbing on the bathroom floor of the courthouse. it was the worst deposition the prosecuting attorney and counselor had seen. both apologized to me for not making it stop.

who will love me? â€¦i asked myself trembling hysterically in the witness stand.  subpoenaed as a character witness in another victims trial i was at a loss for words. the judge chose to announce a recess.

who will love me? â€¦i asked myself as the defense attorney openly discussed my sexual history in front of the jury. his final plea, â€œmiss mcdaniel laid on her back to receive (insert predators name here.)â€ my heart sank.
who will love me? â€¦i asked myself as i found out his church and family paid for an attorney to appeal his 12-year to life sentence. surely his god did not love me.
who will love me? â€¦i asked myself after my boyfriend said he had been advised to â€œmake sureâ€ he can â€œdealâ€ with my trauma and meâ€¦ for-ev-er. he could not deal.
who will love me? â€¦i asked myself as i hid parts of my life from family and friends. once i lied to my cousin about needing to study. she had no clue i was in a different city prepping for trial.

and we wonder why victims wait days, months, and years to speak up and report?! it is the road less traveled because it is treacherous to navigate. personally my mind began to play tricks on me by believing all of the horrible accusations made by attorneysâ€™. i experienced spiritual trauma, a wound so deep it is hard to find words to explain.  my body was objectified and humiliated in front of a jury and pews of strangers. navigating how to build meaningful relationships in the midst of it all was near impossible. this is why #ibelievesurvivors  #isupportsurvivors #metoo";;en;#ibelievesurvivors, #isupportsurvivors, #metoo;;;;;0;;love.melissa.ann;Melissa Ann

336624;instagram;2018-09-29 16:10:04;FALSE;"itâ€™s been a hard, exhausting and emotional week. between the #kavanaughhearings and the anniversary of my own worst assault, part of me just wants to shut out the world and go to sleep for days. but then i remember that i am a survivor - iâ€™m still here, breathing, living. i honor my need for rest, but i also owe it to myself to keep going and to thrive.

i know iâ€™m not alone in feeling stirred up by these events this week. our collective pain and trauma has been triggered over and over again, and sometimes it feels like it will never end. but from our pain comes the courage so many have shown in speaking out and creating change. we will not break, and we will not be silenced.

if you are a survivor of sexual assault, harassment or abuse - i see you, i hear you, i believe you. it is not your fault, and you are not alone. remember to be kind and gentle with yourself - take a break from the news, go for a walk, reach out to a trusted loved one. and if you need any extra support, leave a comment or send me a message, i have tons of resources!

336626;instagram;2018-09-29 16:10:57;FALSE;"this week has been difficult for so many of us.

but what it did for me was give me hope that we are opening up broader conversations, maybe even listening to women, even if itâ€™s just a little bit more than we did before the #metoo movement began.

iâ€™ve witnessed a lot of courageous, brave, heroic, patriotic acts this week from women like dr. ford and ana maria archila and marie gallagher (the elevator women who confronted senator flake). but where does this leave our kids? the next generation of victims and rapists?
will they know that no means no? will they know personal boundaries? will they feel safe enough to report it? will they listen better than we have?? so much worry.

dylan and i spent a good amount of time this week talking about consent and only touching others when they want to be touched, asking permission and giving permission- from a hug, to a kiss, to play fighting, to tickling, all of it.

336627;instagram;2018-09-29 16:10:58;FALSE;"my daughter was harassed at school the other day ğŸ’” the night before, she carefully made sure she was following the dress code by not wearing shorts that were too short, straps that weren't too skinny on her tank top, and no midriff showing. she felt so proud and confident in her self expression and creative fashion statement! she looked so great that i even took her picture that morning! when i picked her up early to go get her braces, she walked up completely deflated, holding back tears... 'you look like you're in a strip down group'.

these are the comments she received throughout the day from the boys in her class. assault/rape culture is perpetuated by complacency and ignorance. its as if the adults of the world are plugging their ears with their fingers, closing their eyes, shouting 'la la la la la...can't hear you...'. flash forward a few years, and guess who's now moved on from snide little comments in the fourth grade to cornering girls in the high school hallways, pushing them into bedrooms, and locking the doors? its the same boys, who grow to be sorry excuses of adult boys who lie, and gaslight, and deny their sickening behaviors. frankly, i'm appalled and ashamed and disappointed- like many millions of others. .

shame on anyone who actually believes that cutting words like the ones my daughter suffered in hearing are 'just things kids say', as if they aren't calculated and aimed to harm. im still waiting for a reply to the email i sent the principle. im taking names. i will file police reports. i will fight for my daughters and sons. we don't turn the other cheek in this family. #metoo my loves, #metoo

336644;instagram;2018-09-29 16:18:24;FALSE;"#metoo began as a movement that was meant to empower those in minority groups to speak up and own their rights to be and feel safe no matter what.

the point is to unite both men and women, both non minority and minority groups.  the point is to gain universal understanding, compassion and healing.
i was molested by three people that i â€œshouldâ€ have been able to trust: my music manager, my chiropractor and a someone who was giving me a pedicure at a salon on rodeo drive (not kidding).

and then thereâ€™s a point when you kick into #survivalmode and you purposefully donâ€™t fight or make a scene so that you can get out alive and hopefully with the least amount of damage done.
thatâ€™s the problem right there - those crucial moments when the mind goes into shock instead of fight or flight.

those moments are the moments that a purpetrator can misread as a green light and ultimately can rationalize in their own mind that itâ€™s okay. when if they were to listen to their intuition they would know that itâ€™s not.

the progress forward to me is not â€œno means no.â€ because, #duh.  the progress forward is that â€œunivited means univited.â€ there shouldnâ€™t be a sexual advance without a verbal invitation (unless itâ€™s in an already established relationship).

being in berlin has me reflecting a lot about walls, borders, glass ceilings, and all we are doing as a movement to break them down, all the while creating the world we seek to live and thrive in. from refugee resettlement to sexual violence to all the intersections in between, from dc to berlin, from my experience to yours, i see you, i hear you, i believe you, i honor you. and i love you, so fiercely. i so often wonder when they will be tired of fighting us, of hurting us, of using us, of seeing through us. but then i remember how much i continue to fight myself, to tell myself that my experience is invalid, and to push people away from helping me to create this world i so desperately desire to be a part of. itâ€™s been a really hard week, but in the end we have one another and we hold one another, and in each otherâ€™s arms know that we are free. we are diamonds. â¤ï¸

we rise up together. we rise up with love. you had better believe us.
now please vote in the mother fucking midterms. please!!!!!!!!!!!!

336685;instagram;2018-09-29 16:29:44;FALSE;"it is never easy to speak up about sexual harassment and assault when the odds are against you. on a personal note, i have felt lonely and scared about what i share because it has been manipulated to support lies and privilege. however, i know my truth. so, i pray everyday that society fights harder to support anyone who speak up around sexual assault and sexual harassment from anyone. my healing allows me to lean on the people that support me, pray for me, give me a shoulder to cry on and a safe space for my anger. this process has also made me remove myself from certain people and things that no longer serve me.

to all the people who speak up against the violent act of sexual assault and sexual harassment, we got this! keep that vishuddha throat chakra active. this society has a long way to go and our fight will strengthens us.

this week has been full of triggers for those of us who experienced sexual assualt. we may have discovered wounds that we have thought were healed still require our intention. some of us may have found that we had suppressed an experience similar to dr. ford's and her testimony brought it to the foreground.

the triggers may have been for other individuals who may have knowingly or unknowingly caused someone trauma. not sure what the consequences may be, how the person was traumatized, or how to sit with all that is going on.

the truth is we as a community we are coming to terms with the fact that we all are victims of rape culture. some of us sit in the middle in a neutral position but many of us sit at one of the extreme ends of the spectrum.
we need a lot to process this all-admission , apologies, forgiveness, detox, therapy and much more.
believing someone does not change the system. action does.
as we navigate it all and find the process we need to heal make sure you take breaks from media, people, and things that bring you to unhealthy space.
protect your mind, body, and spirit.
i know because i have been challenged by it for the better part of my life.
who you want to be, and your purpose.

336722;instagram;2018-09-29 16:41:57;FALSE;"this week was raw, gut-wrenching, inspiring, heartbreaking and emotionally charged. this week was also a powerful reminder of how we can reclaim and fully stand in our feminine power. so where do we go from here? my takeaways:

stop apologizing for who you are. it's so easy to get trapped in cycles of self-blame, doubt and questioning our decisions. standing in your authentic truth means not letting anyone make you feel any less than who  you are or casting doubt or confusion when you know you are right.

speak, shout and broadcast your truth. it's not enough to just show up authentically. if you see something that's wrong, say it. speak up for women who don't have a voice. share your own experiences of injustice. share your story so that others will have the courage to also speak their truth. start conversations about consent with your neighbors and children.

love yourself and your body. you can be as sexual as you want. you can hang out in your swimsuit all day long. celebrate your body. love it. don't ever let yourself be defined by what society or men dictate to be the ""perfect"" body. create your own standards and remember that your  self worth comes from within.

build a bridge for other women. this week has forced me to take a hard look at how i'm supporting my sisters and women facing economic and social injustice all over the world. remember that there are still places in this world where women are killed for speaking their truth and standing up for what's right. let's stand by them.

i could go on and on but if nothing else, this week has helped me see how powerful our stories are when we come together. how are you feeling  after this week? ------------------------------------------

a starless night seemed apt for how i feel at this time. for my brain makes its own stars, like a concussion and migraine and i've been punched in the face ten times and have fallen to the ground and hold my head.
to be triggered is to have a starless night. everything around you turns dark suddenly, quickly, and yet your mind is so bright you do not need the stars in the sky to illuminate your path.
to illuminate your path you have the moon of trauma glare down, the sun behind it beats you with flashbacks and you do not need stars in the sky, the star of the show is your post traumatic stress.

it seems apt that today would be a starless sky, as words fly and other people's trauma resurfaces, and we must band together. be the stars. illuminate the path for those who cannot do it alone. we should not do it alone.
tonight we band and make the stars.
watch us. blazing balls of fire.
tonight we are the stars in the sky. - k.h

336741;instagram;2018-09-29 16:52:21;FALSE;"these past few days have felt like an emotional rollercoasterâ€¦ its taken me days to put it into words. like so many other survivors of sexual trauma, i have relived my own experiences as i watched dr. ford muster all of her courage and strength to speak her truth on a world-wide stage for all to see. it felt like riding the heavy and relentless waves of deep sadness, fear, anger, rage, shame, frustration, hopelessnessâ€¦ and then the spark of grief that inspired my own courage and bravery to rise within me.

dr. fordâ€¦ thank you for showing us with your words and your actions what courage and bravery look like in a world when the deck is stacked against you. despite the risks to yourself, your family and your future, you did it anywaysâ€¦ you gave a voice to all survivors who have been shamed, guilted, doubted into silence.
despite the outcomeâ€¦ we will continue to healâ€¦ and we will continue to riseâ€¦ and we will do it together.

to all survivorsâ€¦ i believe youâ€¦ this was never your faultâ€¦ you never need to doubt yourselfâ€¦ your gut knows the truth even though many may doubt you or minimize your experienceâ€¦ you donâ€™t need to fight to prove itâ€¦ your pain is your proofâ€¦ your pain is real... it is just as real as your strength, your courage and your power to heal yourself from the inside out.
i stand with youâ€¦ for youâ€¦ and in service to you in your healing journey.

was a virgin in college waiting to meet a nice guy that was worth the time. i partied, i was always around men, but always felt i had a handle. until one night we had a party. i woke up the next morning after what ended up being a black out night in a pool of my own blood naked with some dude next to me. i only knew him to be a friend of a friend. i didn't know what to do. i immediately started to blame myself. i drank too much. was i flirting? i must have lead him on? i continued to blame myself as i cried in the shower as he yelled ""bye"" through the door while leaving. what did i do to myself? turns out nothing. maybe i drank and flirted but it does not give a right for someone to take advantage of another while black out drunk. you'd think all the blood would be a hindrance. i let this go, and it def gave me issues i had to work through the years thankfully i never had to really see him again. he prob is married w/ kids and career now. maybe he's matured and never hurt another again. i'm not going to take the time to search him down and get at him for what happened now. however if he became a public figure, was running for a public office, or say appointed to be a supreme court justice, you better believe i'd speak up. a person of power in the public eye that has influence over our public, should be held accountable for anything they have done in the past as even a view of their nature, morals. even to have the ability of admittance with remorse and humility instead of passing blame would show some decency. i don't want the ""so sorry""s from sharing this i want this to help others understand victims' perspective.";;en;#metoo;;;;;0;;cindope;Cindy 336810;instagram;2018-09-29 17:13:57;FALSE;even when we think we've healed something, an experience is presented that seems to bring it all back up. does it mean we're back at square one and all our progress has vanished? no.
we can learn to see this as an opportunity to heal different aspects of our trauma, because it's really these neglected aspects that are causing the resonant experience of triggering.
each day, i work with women (and a few men!), focused on healing. self-healing is my most intense passion.

this week, i've learned even more deeply to embrace flow. to say to myself ""it's ok that i'm not perfectly healed (that does not exist!) it's ok that i'm in pain. it's ok that i've neglected my trauma of sexual abuse because i was focused on deeply healing other personally more intense traumas."" i hear so many lovely people in this community talk about ""clearing"" experiences and energy as though we just burn some sage and boom! i've definitely used this term before too so it's all good. ğŸ˜‚ but we all know it's not like that.
the truth is that things don't just ""clear"", they heal. we have the ability to transmute energies of trauma and pain into love.
am i healed? yes. am i still healing? yes.
embrace the pain. heart wide open.
love to you and thank you for being here. thank you for loving and healing yourself. through healing ourselves, we'll heal the world. ğŸ’•

we can learn to see this as an oppounity to heal different aspects of our trauma, because it is really these neglected aspects that are causing the resot experience of triggering.
each day, i work with women (and a few men!), focused on healing. self-healing is my most intense passion.

this week, i have learned even more deeply to embrace flow. to say to myself ""it is ok that i am not perfectly healed (that does not exist!) it is ok that i am in pain. it is ok that i have neglected my trauma of sexual abuse because i was focused on deeply healing other personally more intense traumas."" i hear so many lovely people in this community talk about ""clearing"" experiences and energy as though we just burn some sage and boom! i have definitely used this term before too so it is all good. ğŸ˜‚ but we all know it is not like that.
the truth is that things do not just ""clear"", they heal. we have the ability to transmute energies of trauma and pain into love.
am i healed? yes. am i still healing? yes.
embrace the pain. hea wide open.
love to you and thank you for being here. thank you for loving and healing yourself. through healing ourselves, we'll heal the world. ğŸ’•

we were friends for years. we had classes together, we studied together, we hung out together, we were there to see each other through happy and sad times. you were a nice guy, and we ended up with a lot of mutual friends; none of them expected what happened either. it was years before you tried to force yourself on me. years before you breathed sour air into my face while you tried to hold me down, telling me i owe you this, as i fought against you. if you hadn't been so drunk, you would have succeeded. when i was able to throw you off, you started yelling at me, calling me names and once again telling me i owe this to you. others heard and came to help, and you still kept trying to come at me with your friend holding you back. you had to be half-dragged out of my house when my roommate threatened to call the police, your yells still directed at me. i was too numb to do anything when others got involved.. being a woman, these days, you know it's only a matter of time before someone tries something; it feels inevitable. that's not what broke me. you broke me with you tarnished every moment we had spent as friends. you broke me when you planted a seed of doubt in every friendship i have with someone of the opposite sex. you broke me when you made me forever wonder who else might turn out like you. i hate you for that. #metoo";;en;#metoo;;;;;0;;kae_berry_;Kaelyn Berryman;;0;False;5;0;0;42;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/79698faf9f4693d33d7619d579f4f9a4/5D07D41E/t51.2885-15/e35/41646419_1862705823813927_358636276255619538_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"trigger warning: sexual assault .

as a woman, i have grown tired of striving to be less...to eat less, to dumb myself down, to weigh less, to grab the pink weights and lift less, to do everything...less. after finding fitness, and an amazing community of strong and empowered women, i learned to strive to be more. to go harder, to lift heavier, to be stronger, to be a fucking power house of fierceness! with all the kavanaugh stuff on the news i felt the need to share my feelings. i'm not going to share my story, as i don't find it necessary to do so. i will, however, share how i deal...why i do what i do...in hopes of inspiring others do do the same. pushing myself to my limits physically is empowering. it makes me feel safe. it makes me feel strong.
here's a workout dedicated to the pain and suffering you may have dealt with in the past, at the hands of someone else. .
round one is dedicated to the times you blamed yourself.
round two is dedicated to the times you felt no one would belive you.
round three is dedicated to the times you convinced yourself it wasn't a big deal. .
round four is dedicated to the times you felt guilt, anxiety, and stress.
round five is dedicated to the times you pretended nothing happened.
round six is dedicated to the amazing strength you now have, to the amazing woman you have become. .
now dust yourself off, because you are a fucking bad ass fighter. i believe you. i believe her. #metoo .
tag a friend who could use the support.
